\section{When to use \code{dhs_read()}}{


Use \code{dhs_read()} only when you have a parquet archive that follows the
layout below. The archive is what makes multi-country, multi-year,
multi-recode discovery (\code{dhs_read(file_type = "GE", country_code = ...)})
and the \code{run_mbg_pipeline()} workflow possible.

If you have a \strong{single DHS file} (\code{.dta}, \code{.csv}, \code{.rds}, \code{.sav}, ...),
you do \strong{not} need \code{dhs_read()} or a parquet archive at all. Read the
file with \code{\link[sntutils:read]{sntutils::read()}} (or \code{haven::read_dta()}) and pass the
resulting data frame straight to any \verb{calc_*_dhs()} function:

\if{html}{\out{<div class="sourceCode r">}}\preformatted{kr <- sntutils::read("TGKR81FL.DTA")   # or .csv, .rds, .sav, ...
ge <- sntutils::read("TGGE8AFL.dta")
fever <- calc_fever_dhs(dhs_kr = kr, gps_data = ge,
                        shapefile = shp_admin,
                        admin_level = c("adm0", "adm1"))
}\if{html}{\out{</div>}}

Every \verb{calc_*_dhs()} estimator accepts a plain data frame - the recode-
specific reader is just convenience.
